WEBVTT

00:08.000 --> 00:10.300
DAPHNE: Wow, look at you.
- Ha-ha-ha.

00:10.600 --> 00:13.600
You look just... like him.

00:14.900 --> 00:18.000
Oh, Daphne, come on, huh?

00:18.400 --> 00:22.000
The theme this evening
is to come dressed as your hero.

00:24.400 --> 00:26.200
Fidel Castro.

00:27.400 --> 00:28.900
Sigmund Freud.

00:30.100 --> 00:32.200
Daphne, don't you think
that bowl is a little bit small

00:32.500 --> 00:34.900
- for a whole night of trick-or-treaters?
- I don't think so.

00:35.100 --> 00:37.400
Children in the building
are too scared to ring our bell.

00:37.700 --> 00:41.300
- Why is that?
- They're afraid of "Old Man Crane."

00:41.600 --> 00:43.000
[CHUCKLES]

00:43.200 --> 00:47.000
- Poor Dad. Ha, ha.
- It's not him, Dr. Crane. It's you.

00:48.700 --> 00:51.100
What? I'm Old Man Crane?

00:51.600 --> 00:53.900
Good Lord, I have tousled
every young head in this building

00:54.200 --> 00:57.700
- from the laundry room to the rooftop.
- Yeah, apparently that's how it started.

00:58.000 --> 01:00.200
They think you're feeling
to see if their brains are ripe.

01:02.100 --> 01:03.200
How do you know all this?

01:03.500 --> 01:04.900
They have a whole rhyme
about you:

01:05.099 --> 01:06.900
[SINGING]
<i>Old Man Crane, Old Man Crane</i>

01:07.200 --> 01:10.200
<i>Make him mad</i>
<i>And he'll eat your brain</i>

01:12.100 --> 01:13.500
That's absurd.

01:13.800 --> 01:15.900
How do children
get such crazy ideas?

01:16.200 --> 01:17.600
[TO Y WEAPONS BEEPING]

01:17.700 --> 01:21.000
Whoa, hey, hey,
keep it down, will you?

01:21.400 --> 01:23.900
- We're just playing.
MARTIN: I know.

01:24.300 --> 01:27.000
But you know how
Old Man Crane gets.

01:27.300 --> 01:31.700
Especially on Halloween,
or as he calls it, "harvest time."

01:32.100 --> 01:34.100
[ALL SCREAMING]

01:40.000 --> 01:42.400
[FOOTSTEPS]

01:43.500 --> 01:44.800
Fras?

01:48.600 --> 01:52.300
Hello... baseball man.

01:52.700 --> 01:53.700
[LAUGHS]

01:54.000 --> 01:56.600
Oh, come on. Joe DiMaggio.

01:56.800 --> 01:58.400
- You know who he is?
- Of course.

01:58.500 --> 02:01.000
Joe DiMaggio was married
to Marilyn Monroe,

02:01.400 --> 02:03.500
who was also married
to Arthur Miller, the playwright,

02:03.800 --> 02:05.600
who wrote <i>Death of a Salesman,</i>
<i>The Crucible.</i>

02:05.800 --> 02:09.000
You see, Dad, I know a lot more
about baseball than you think.

02:09.400 --> 02:11.200
How does this party game
of yours work?

02:11.500 --> 02:13.700
Is it like charades?
Because I don't like charades.

02:14.000 --> 02:16.500
Oh, no, no, Dad,
it's actually much better.

02:16.700 --> 02:20.000
I have devised some questions
that we will answer as our heroes.

02:20.200 --> 02:22.500
What better way to learn
about each other than to explore

02:22.700 --> 02:25.300
the personalities of those
who most inspire us, hmm?

02:25.700 --> 02:27.800
Couldn't we just play charades?

02:29.400 --> 02:32.300
You know, if this evening
goes really well,

02:32.700 --> 02:35.200
I may consider marketing
my little invention.

02:35.500 --> 02:37.400
It's a welcome change
from those theme parties

02:37.600 --> 02:39.200
where someone gets murdered.

02:39.400 --> 02:40.800
Yeah, it could still happen.

02:41.900 --> 02:43.800
[TELEPHONE RINGING]

02:46.500 --> 02:47.600
Hello?

02:47.800 --> 02:49.900
Gil, good heavens.

02:50.100 --> 02:52.300
Shouldn't you
be on your way by now?

02:53.200 --> 02:55.800
Well, yes, of course
we'll be playing my little game.

02:57.000 --> 02:59.200
Oh, you don't sound sick.

03:00.100 --> 03:01.800
Oh, now I hear it. Oh...

03:02.400 --> 03:03.700
All right, feel better.

03:03.900 --> 03:05.700
- Isn't that your eighth cancellation?
- Yes.

03:05.900 --> 03:06.800
[DOORBELL RINGS]

03:07.100 --> 03:10.100
Must be something
going around at the office, hmm.

03:13.300 --> 03:14.900
- Hi.
- Hi.

03:15.200 --> 03:18.800
- Hey, it's Joe DiMaggio.
- Ma'am.

03:20.100 --> 03:22.700
- I see you've brought a little puppy.
- Yes.

03:23.100 --> 03:26.100
We've been trick-or-treating
all afternoon, and she's exhausted.

03:26.400 --> 03:29.100
Strange. Children in our building
haven't started trick-or-treating.

03:29.300 --> 03:32.100
Are you kidding? I just rode up
the elevator with five Britney Spears

03:32.300 --> 03:34.200
and a sweaty Harry Potter.

03:35.600 --> 03:38.200
I'm gonna go put her down
in your room. Can I change there?

03:38.500 --> 03:39.700
Well, as you know, Roz:

03:40.000 --> 03:41.500
[IN AUSTRIAN ACCENT]
Change can only occur

03:41.700 --> 03:44.700
after years of hard work
<i>und</i> analysis.

03:45.400 --> 03:48.100
- Gonna be a hell of a party.
- Yeah.

03:51.700 --> 03:54.500
What the heck
are you supposed to be?

03:55.200 --> 03:56.500
Reginald Dwight.

03:56.800 --> 03:59.400
You may know me
as Sir Elton John.

03:59.700 --> 04:01.100
FRASIER [IN NORMAL VOICE]:
Daphne, I must say,

04:01.300 --> 04:04.100
I hardly think of Elton John
as an heroic figure.

04:04.400 --> 04:07.700
Yes, he is. He's been a great
musician for over 30 years.

04:08.000 --> 04:10.300
There's also his charity work
and his knighthood.

04:11.300 --> 04:14.400
Well, I never thought of it that way,
which is the point of this evening.

04:14.600 --> 04:16.500
Thank you for putting thought
into your costume

04:16.800 --> 04:18.899
rather than just throwing on
something frivolous.

04:20.500 --> 04:22.100
Ta-da!

04:24.500 --> 04:27.200
MARTIN:
Wow, Roz, you look great!

04:29.300 --> 04:31.800
Oh, Roz, are you serious?

04:32.100 --> 04:35.200
- What?
- Well, your hero is Wonder Woman?

04:35.600 --> 04:38.000
You're supposed to come dressed
as the person you most admire,

04:38.200 --> 04:39.400
whom you most wish to emulate.

04:39.600 --> 04:43.000
I'm not even sure
you can do that to the flag.

04:45.000 --> 04:48.500
I'm sorry. When you said hero,
I thought you meant superhero.

04:48.700 --> 04:51.200
Yes, and when you saw me
dressed in a beard with a cigar,

04:51.500 --> 04:53.700
what superhero did you think I was,
hmm?

04:55.300 --> 04:57.700
That butler who cooked for Batman.

05:01.000 --> 05:03.700
Speaking of which, could you help me
bring out cheese, Wonder Woman?

05:04.300 --> 05:06.500
I'd be glad to, Elton John.

05:07.200 --> 05:09.200
[TELEPHONE RINGING]

05:11.300 --> 05:12.700
Hello?

05:13.000 --> 05:14.400
Kenny.

05:14.700 --> 05:18.100
Gosh, don't you think
you should've left by now?

05:18.500 --> 05:20.600
Well, actually, there have been
a few cancellations,

05:20.800 --> 05:23.700
so that will allow us to delve
even deeper into our psyches.

05:25.400 --> 05:27.500
Really? What kind of sick?

05:28.700 --> 05:31.100
Oh, gosh, that sounds horrible.

05:31.400 --> 05:34.700
Yes, all right.
Well, um, take care.

05:35.000 --> 05:38.100
You know, we might be wise
to take some echinacea.

05:40.400 --> 05:41.800
[DOORBELL RINGS]

05:45.500 --> 05:46.800
Somebody get me a beer!

05:47.000 --> 05:48.600
MARTIN:
Ah!

05:52.900 --> 05:55.100
Niles, uh, what in the world...?

05:55.400 --> 05:57.700
Well, you said dress as your hero.
Hello, Dad.

05:58.000 --> 05:59.200
[MARTIN LAUGHS]

06:01.800 --> 06:05.200
Holy moly, Niles,
this is unbelievable!

06:05.600 --> 06:07.700
- You like it?
- Oh, I love it!

06:08.000 --> 06:10.900
Ha! But Frasier said
to come as your hero,

06:11.100 --> 06:12.900
not as the handsomest man
in the world.

06:13.200 --> 06:15.200
[LAUGHING]

06:19.100 --> 06:21.400
Niles, I thought you were
going to come as Carl Jung.

06:21.700 --> 06:23.700
- I changed my mind.
- But the idea of this evening

06:24.000 --> 06:26.700
is to come as a classic hero,
someone who truly inspires you.

06:27.000 --> 06:28.300
No offence, Dad, it's...

06:28.600 --> 06:31.200
You know, someone of truly
unquestioned greatness.

06:31.500 --> 06:33.300
- Again, no offence, Dad.
MARTIN: Mm-hm.

06:34.000 --> 06:36.300
Blow it out your whistle. No offence.

06:37.500 --> 06:41.800
- Oh, my goodness. Oh, Niles.
- Oh, isn't that the cutest thing?

06:42.200 --> 06:43.900
What the heck
are you supposed to be?

06:44.200 --> 06:45.700
That's exactly what I said.

06:45.900 --> 06:47.800
[LAUGHING]

06:49.600 --> 06:52.500
FRASIER: Well, I guess
we have a full complement.

06:52.800 --> 06:54.500
We may as well get on
to the main event.

06:54.700 --> 06:57.600
Wonder Woman, Elton John,
Martin Crane, Joe DiMaggio,

06:58.000 --> 06:59.800
I think you all know each other.
Have a seat,

07:00.000 --> 07:03.700
and we will proceed to a night
of frivolity and enlightenment.

07:04.000 --> 07:06.600
Oh. Oh, Joe,
I insist you take my chair.

07:07.000 --> 07:09.000
Thanks, Marty.

07:09.200 --> 07:12.900
All right then, let's dive
into the question bowl.

07:13.400 --> 07:16.600
Now remember, our job
is to answer these questions

07:17.000 --> 07:18.800
as the people we honour tonight.

07:19.100 --> 07:21.200
Well, what if I'm someone
who just wants to watch TV?

07:21.500 --> 07:22.800
- Can I do that?
- Yeah, can he?

07:23.000 --> 07:24.500
[LAUGHING]

07:25.200 --> 07:28.400
Very amusing. Uh, oh, yes,
I took the liberty of jotting down

07:28.800 --> 07:32.100
a few reminders and regulations
for your edification.

07:32.400 --> 07:34.700
- Here you go, Marty.
- Oh, uh...

07:34.900 --> 07:36.600
Niles, you don't really
have to drink that.

07:36.900 --> 07:38.800
I'm already wearing
black shoes with white socks.

07:39.100 --> 07:40.200
I may as well go all the way.

07:40.400 --> 07:42.400
[MARTIN LAUGHS]

07:44.600 --> 07:47.500
All right, question number one.

07:48.000 --> 07:53.400
The inaugural question in the
first game ever of Hero Worship.

07:53.700 --> 07:57.300
Copyright, Frasier Crane,
boilerplate, boilerplate.

07:58.300 --> 08:01.000
As your hero...

08:02.500 --> 08:05.600
..."please share your reaction
to the Human Genome Project.

08:05.900 --> 08:10.500
Not only as a scientific venture, but as
a regulatory challenge to governments,

08:10.800 --> 08:12.500
foreign and domestic."

08:13.600 --> 08:15.300
- No.
- Are you insane?

08:15.600 --> 08:18.700
All right, all right, maybe we'll just
save that for the lightning round.

08:19.000 --> 08:20.300
Well...

08:23.400 --> 08:26.100
As your hero...

08:27.300 --> 08:31.700
..."describe the most significant
relationship in your life." Hmm?

08:32.100 --> 08:33.299
NILES:
Oh, all right.

08:33.500 --> 08:35.900
I'll tell you what, I'll go first.

08:39.799 --> 08:41.700
[IN AUSTRIAN ACCENT]
Though it is common

08:42.900 --> 08:47.700
for a parent to deeply impact
the life of her child,

08:48.200 --> 08:50.900
consider the exponential power

08:51.100 --> 08:54.700
that parent wields
when she loves one of the children

08:54.900 --> 08:57.100
above the rest,

08:57.400 --> 09:02.400
singling him out as "my golden Sigi,"
and referring to...

09:02.900 --> 09:04.300
[IN UNISON]
Boring.

09:04.500 --> 09:06.500
[LAUGHING]

09:08.400 --> 09:10.500
Really, Frasier,
mother, Freud, we get it.

09:10.800 --> 09:12.300
[IN NORMAL VOICE]
All right, very well.

09:12.600 --> 09:15.000
Now, in the first of many wrinkles,
the game will proceed

09:15.300 --> 09:16.900
counterclockwise.

09:17.200 --> 09:19.900
- Joe?
- Oh, all right. Ahem.

09:20.300 --> 09:22.700
Well, even though I had a big family,
I'd have to say

09:23.000 --> 09:27.600
that my most important relationship
was probably with Marilyn Monroe.

09:28.000 --> 09:29.000
NILES:
Ooh.

09:29.300 --> 09:31.100
Although I might've
been married before that.

09:31.200 --> 09:33.200
I'm not sure.

09:33.700 --> 09:37.200
[IMITATING ELTON JOHN]
I wrote a song about Marilyn Monroe.

09:37.500 --> 09:40.400
"Candle in the Wind."

09:44.100 --> 09:45.800
Yes, that's very good.

09:48.700 --> 09:53.000
Can't believe I'm saying this,
but, Wonder Woman, you're next.

09:54.300 --> 09:57.900
Okay, uh, my greatest relationship

09:58.200 --> 10:02.200
was with my alter ego,
who was a nurse in the Army,

10:02.500 --> 10:03.900
and her name
was Diana Prince, and...

10:04.100 --> 10:08.600
Hey, I wrote a song
about Princess Diana.

10:10.200 --> 10:13.500
And it was the same song
I wrote about Marilyn Monroe.

10:14.700 --> 10:17.300
- That's weird.
- Really weird.

10:17.700 --> 10:20.000
You would never think
that two such disparate characters

10:20.300 --> 10:22.800
across half a century of time
could be connected like that.

10:23.100 --> 10:24.900
That's because
they're not connected!

10:27.200 --> 10:30.000
The song was written about
Princess Diana, not Diana Prince!

10:30.600 --> 10:34.200
- Still, it's a pretty odd coincidence.
FRASIER: It's not a coincidence at all!

10:34.600 --> 10:36.000
It's two names
that barely sound alike

10:36.200 --> 10:39.200
when one of them
is pronounced in reverse order!

10:39.600 --> 10:41.200
Now, if we could just return
to my game...

10:41.500 --> 10:45.500
It says right here that one of
the objectives is lively conversation.

10:45.800 --> 10:47.800
- What we're having.
- I know my game's objectives,

10:48.100 --> 10:51.400
and they do not include
this nascent migraine!

10:53.700 --> 10:56.200
All right, Martin Crane,

10:57.200 --> 11:01.900
why don't you tell us about
your most significant relationship?

11:04.000 --> 11:05.500
Alrighty.

11:05.800 --> 11:11.100
In 1952, I met a woman
named Hester Palmer,

11:11.500 --> 11:13.200
and even though
she's been gone 14 years,

11:13.400 --> 11:16.300
she was not only
the greatest relationship in my life,

11:16.600 --> 11:18.600
but also the greatest blessing.

11:20.400 --> 11:22.400
I miss her every day.

11:22.600 --> 11:24.300
You're a good boy, Niles.

11:24.900 --> 11:27.200
BOTH:
Aw...

11:29.200 --> 11:31.300
Niles, could I see you
in the kitchen?

11:35.300 --> 11:38.200
Did Niles finally get here?
Where is that boy genius?

11:38.600 --> 11:40.000
Yes, okay.

11:40.300 --> 11:43.200
- Dad, could I see you in the kitchen?
- Why's he looking at me?

11:43.400 --> 11:45.600
- I'm not Freud's dad.
- Martin Crane!

11:51.600 --> 11:53.600
It doesn't take Freud
to see what's going on here.

11:53.900 --> 11:54.900
What are you talking about?

11:55.100 --> 11:57.000
Oh, your little ploy
is working out brilliantly.

11:57.200 --> 11:59.100
Not only have you stolen
my thunder as host,

11:59.400 --> 12:02.500
you've also won the approval
you so desperately crave from Dad.

12:02.800 --> 12:04.000
It's not about craving approval.

12:04.300 --> 12:06.600
This is about honouring someone
I respect and admire.

12:06.900 --> 12:09.800
The fact that you're threatened by it
speaks volumes about your insecurity.

12:10.100 --> 12:11.300
Don't you turn this on me.

12:11.600 --> 12:13.500
I am comfortable
with my relationship with Dad.

12:13.900 --> 12:16.700
Well, then you should be glad
that he's having fun,

12:17.000 --> 12:19.600
which rarely happens
at your parties.

12:19.800 --> 12:21.400
Or mine.

12:22.800 --> 12:26.100
So why don't we both take pride
in that and just be happy for him?

12:26.400 --> 12:29.600
Or as Dad would say, "Shut your big
bazoo and stop thinking so much."

12:30.000 --> 12:31.100
[LAUGHS]

12:33.000 --> 12:34.300
Oh, let's play Scattergories.

12:34.600 --> 12:36.500
Do you have one of those
murder-mystery games?

12:36.600 --> 12:39.100
So that's it, then?
The party's over?

12:39.500 --> 12:42.100
- What? We're just getting started.
- You're not playing my game.

12:42.300 --> 12:44.300
This is chaos.
We're people in costumes drinking.

12:44.600 --> 12:46.300
Amen!

12:47.300 --> 12:49.900
Here, Roz, uh, would you
take a picture of Marty Crane

12:50.100 --> 12:53.700
with his hero, Joe DiMaggio.

12:54.400 --> 12:55.400
[LAUGHING]

12:55.600 --> 12:58.700
- It'll make a great Christmas card.
FRASIER: Yeah, good idea, Dad.

12:59.000 --> 13:01.400
You've already ruined Halloween.
Why not ruin Christmas too?

13:01.700 --> 13:03.800
NILES: Frasier, come on, relax.
We're just having fun.

13:04.000 --> 13:06.800
Hey, have a beer.
It really takes the edge off.

13:07.600 --> 13:10.700
- Yeah, don't be a spoilsport.
- Spoilsport?

13:11.100 --> 13:14.900
I haven't spoiled anything.
I'm not the bad guy here.

13:15.100 --> 13:17.100
[SCREAMING]

13:24.800 --> 13:25.900
[BO Y LAUGHS]

13:26.200 --> 13:27.400
[CHILDREN GASPING]

13:27.600 --> 13:29.900
JUSTIN:
Hey, that's mine!

13:30.700 --> 13:34.400
- Did that boy just steal your candy?
- Yeah.

13:34.700 --> 13:37.700
If you tell me his name,
I'll go speak to his parents for you.

13:38.000 --> 13:39.600
His parents are my parents.

13:39.900 --> 13:42.100
He's my brother.

13:42.700 --> 13:44.300
FRASIER:
Ah...

13:45.400 --> 13:48.100
- It isn't easy having a brother, is it?
- No.

13:49.600 --> 13:51.500
They can be selfish
and thoughtless.

13:51.800 --> 13:54.700
- And butt-faces.
- Butt-faces, yes.

13:55.000 --> 13:57.800
And butt-faces too.

14:02.200 --> 14:07.800
But you know what might
put things right?

14:08.200 --> 14:09.100
What?

14:10.200 --> 14:16.700
The smallest pinch
of fibreglass in his bed.

14:18.800 --> 14:22.200
It'll get under his skin. It'll itch for days,
with no clue how it got there.

14:22.400 --> 14:24.900
Have you seen those spare rolls
of insulation in the basement?

14:25.400 --> 14:27.400
- That sounds pretty mean.
- Huh.

14:28.300 --> 14:30.500
He stole your candy, didn't he?

14:31.200 --> 14:33.800
And embarrassed you
in front of your friends?

14:34.600 --> 14:36.200
I guess.

14:36.400 --> 14:39.200
- But still, he's not so bad.
- Seemed pretty bad a moment ago.

14:39.500 --> 14:41.400
- Well, he was just showing off.
- Ah.

14:41.600 --> 14:47.300
- But most days he's all right.
- Still, the man stole your candy.

14:48.100 --> 14:51.500
And ruined your
much-anticipated evening.

14:51.800 --> 14:54.300
Shouldn't there be repercussions?

14:55.200 --> 14:56.900
Are you okay?

15:00.600 --> 15:02.100
Yes.

15:02.700 --> 15:06.400
I suppose I'm just having
a bit of a temper tantrum, that's all.

15:07.100 --> 15:10.400
- Yeah, I get those too.
- Ha, ha.

15:10.700 --> 15:12.700
Well, I'm going home.

15:13.800 --> 15:16.800
- See you later.
- Yup, see you later.

15:17.800 --> 15:19.700
Say, you know,
maybe I'll go home too.

15:19.900 --> 15:22.000
If your brother
doesn't give back your candy,

15:22.300 --> 15:24.100
you can come trick-or-treating
at my apartment.

15:24.400 --> 15:26.700
I got bags of the stuff.
You can have all you want.

15:27.000 --> 15:28.600
Really? Awesome.

15:28.900 --> 15:31.300
Apartment 1901.

15:32.400 --> 15:34.400
1901?

15:36.300 --> 15:38.800
You're the guy who eats brains.

15:40.300 --> 15:43.400
Now, come on.
If I really ate brains,

15:43.600 --> 15:46.800
children would be disappearing
from the building all the time.

15:47.000 --> 15:49.500
You haven't noticed
anything like that, have you?

15:49.800 --> 15:52.500
- No.
- That's because I don't eat brains.

15:52.700 --> 15:54.500
[CHUCKLES]

15:55.500 --> 15:58.300
Not human brains, anyway.

16:00.100 --> 16:02.400
A nice fresh order of calves' brains
in a <i>beurre noir</i> sauce,

16:02.700 --> 16:04.100
now that would be...

16:06.600 --> 16:07.700
I don't eat brains.

16:07.800 --> 16:09.400
[CHUCKLES]

16:12.000 --> 16:14.500
- All right, stop it.
- What?

16:14.800 --> 16:18.300
I don't wanna watch myself
make out with Elton John.

16:23.400 --> 16:24.400
Hello, all.

16:24.600 --> 16:25.800
- Hey.
NILES: Oh...

16:27.300 --> 16:31.900
I would like to apologise
for my petulant departure.

16:32.400 --> 16:34.500
I just want us to all
enjoy ourselves this evening.

16:34.700 --> 16:38.700
And, Niles, I never should've
questioned your motives

16:39.000 --> 16:40.500
for this wonderful tribute.

16:40.900 --> 16:42.200
Thank you, son.

16:42.500 --> 16:43.900
[BELCHES]

16:45.200 --> 16:47.300
DAPHNE:
It was our fault too, Dr. Crane.

16:47.600 --> 16:51.000
- We didn't give your game a chance.
- Yeah. Let's give it another shot.

16:51.300 --> 16:53.000
Joltin' Joe wouldn't quit,
and neither will I.

16:53.300 --> 16:54.300
[DAPHNE CHUCKLES]

16:54.600 --> 16:56.200
Roz, since you misunderstood
the theme,

16:56.400 --> 17:00.900
I'll tell you what, why don't you answer
this question as your true hero,

17:01.300 --> 17:02.800
whomever that may be.

17:03.500 --> 17:06.900
Actually, I didn't
misunderstand anything.

17:07.300 --> 17:08.800
You made so much fun
of my costume,

17:09.000 --> 17:11.500
I got so embarrassed, so I lied.

17:11.800 --> 17:13.800
Wonder Woman really is my hero.

17:16.500 --> 17:21.099
I mean, she's smart and beautiful,
moral, and totally independent.

17:21.500 --> 17:22.700
And talk about hooters.

17:22.900 --> 17:24.500
[LAUGHING]

17:26.599 --> 17:29.000
Hey, I'd keep that to myself.

17:31.600 --> 17:34.400
Roz, I never should've criticised you.
I am terribly sorry.

17:35.500 --> 17:36.900
- Thank you.
NILES: Oh, Daphne,

17:37.100 --> 17:39.500
- you didn't bring me a brewster.
- I think you've had enough.

17:39.800 --> 17:42.400
Oh, you can never
have enough beer, Jodi.

17:43.300 --> 17:46.100
That's Joe D.

17:47.200 --> 17:50.100
- Niles, I believe that you're next.
NILES: Huh.

17:50.500 --> 17:54.100
Tell us about your hero's
greatest disappointment.

17:55.000 --> 18:01.200
Um... Oh, well, that I never got to take
my kids to see Joe DiMaggio play.

18:01.600 --> 18:05.400
Oh, that's not your fault, Marty.
I retired when they were infants.

18:05.800 --> 18:07.000
Guess it's not that important.

18:07.200 --> 18:10.500
My kids wouldn't know a baseball
if it hit them in the face.

18:11.600 --> 18:12.700
In fact, hm-hm,

18:12.900 --> 18:15.100
that pretty much describes
their one day in Little League.

18:15.400 --> 18:17.000
[LAUGHING]

18:17.300 --> 18:20.500
No offence, Joe,
my kids did not care about baseball.

18:20.800 --> 18:24.300
Hell, they didn't care about
anything that was important to me.

18:24.700 --> 18:26.800
- Hey, now, that's not fair.
NILES: No, no, no, Joe.

18:27.200 --> 18:28.700
I'm saying you and me,
we're regular guys.

18:29.000 --> 18:31.900
You know, we know how to hang out
with regular guys and shoot the breeze

18:32.100 --> 18:36.300
and knock a few back,
but, uh, not my kids.

18:36.600 --> 18:38.800
No, they're too good for that stuff.

18:39.100 --> 18:43.000
They, uh... They got all their fancy
degrees, but they never learned...

18:44.000 --> 18:46.100
...how to be regular guys.

18:47.400 --> 18:49.600
I guess if I had to pick
my two biggest disappointments...

18:49.900 --> 18:51.600
You stop right there.

18:52.900 --> 18:56.000
You will not
put these words in my mouth.

18:56.300 --> 18:58.100
I was always proud of you boys,

18:58.400 --> 19:03.300
and I will not be portrayed as some
drunken, judgemental jackass.

19:08.300 --> 19:10.800
That's why I didn't
dress as you, Dad.

19:17.000 --> 19:19.200
You're a good son, Frasier.

19:21.200 --> 19:23.000
I'll go round up Alice.

19:23.300 --> 19:25.200
Another great party.

19:28.800 --> 19:30.900
I am so sorry. I, uh...

19:31.100 --> 19:35.400
- I don't know what got into me.
- I'd say about six of these.

19:35.600 --> 19:39.800
Everything was so perfect,
and I just... blew it.

19:40.200 --> 19:42.600
L... I feel terrible.

19:42.900 --> 19:46.300
Oh, Niles, why don't you
just go talk to him?

19:46.700 --> 19:50.000
I'm sure I am the last person
he wants to see right now.

19:50.900 --> 19:53.500
Oh, I wouldn't be so sure
about that.

19:53.800 --> 19:55.800
He's not your hero for nothing.

19:58.600 --> 20:01.100
Right. Heh. Thank you, Frasier.

20:01.400 --> 20:03.100
But maybe you should
talk to him as Niles.

20:03.500 --> 20:06.500
Ah, good idea. Heh-heh-heh.

20:06.700 --> 20:07.700
Ow.

20:08.700 --> 20:12.100
- Hey, uh, help me get this wig off.
FRASIER: Fine.

20:12.800 --> 20:14.100
- Ow!
- I'm sorry.

20:14.200 --> 20:15.300
- Ow!
- Ow!

20:15.600 --> 20:18.300
- Ow! Ow! Ow!
- Ow! Stop it! All right.

20:18.600 --> 20:20.000
You put too much spirit gum on it.

20:20.200 --> 20:21.900
I'm gonna need something
to pry it off.

20:22.200 --> 20:23.100
[DOORBELL RINGS]

20:23.300 --> 20:24.800
- I'll get it.
FRASIER: All right.

20:25.000 --> 20:27.400
- Here, try this.
- Oh, thanks, Daphne.

20:27.700 --> 20:29.700
All right, now, come on.
Now, hold still.

20:30.000 --> 20:32.000
NILES: Easy, easy, easy...
- All right, come on.

20:32.600 --> 20:34.100
CHILDREN:
Trick or treat!

20:34.400 --> 20:36.400
DAPHNE:
Oh, how lovely. One moment.

20:36.700 --> 20:39.500
NILES: Wait, you're hurting me!
FRASIER: Because you keep fighting!

20:39.700 --> 20:41.500
[NILES SCREAMS]

20:41.800 --> 20:43.400
[SCREAMING]

20:43.900 --> 20:45.400
No, children, come back!

20:45.700 --> 20:48.800
I've got candy!
